# When "chaos" is actually order: sacred traditions, invisible labor, and who gets to name the body's work

The rhythm Gabrielle Roth called "Chaos" — the wild, head-shaking, full-body-release third movement of her 5Rhythms practice — draws directly from Yoruba sacred drumming traditions, one of the most mathematically precise and spiritually structured musical systems on Earth. That a Western practitioner extracted this tradition, stripped its cosmological framework, and labeled it "chaos" replicates a colonial logic so deeply embedded it has largely gone unexamined within the 5Rhythms community. This same pattern — embodied traditions extracted, decontextualized, renamed, and economically reorganized to benefit those doing the naming — threads through the gender dynamics at Esalen Institute, the exploitation Degas documented in Parisian ballet, and the biomechanics of high heels. Across all four domains, the through-line is the same: **someone's disciplined, sacred, or painful physical labor is made to appear natural, primitive, effortless, or invisible — and the person doing that labor is not the person who profits.**

---

## Babatunde Olatunji's drumming became Roth's "chaos"

The specific musician at the center of the 5Rhythms–Yoruba connection is **Babatunde Olatunji** (1927–2003), the Nigerian master percussionist whose 1960 album *Drums of Passion* — a collection of Yoruba rhythms — sold over five million copies and fundamentally reshaped American audiences' encounter with African music. Olatunji taught at both Esalen Institute and the Omega Institute for Holistic Studies, the same institutions where Roth developed and taught her practice. Liner notes for the Time Capsule Records compilation of Roth's work describe how "as the 'world music' phenomenon unfolded around him, **Olatunji passed into Roth's sphere**, teaching at both Esalen and the Omega Institute in New York City."

The pipeline was not indirect. Two of Olatunji's protégés — **Gordy Ryan** and **Sanga of the Valley** (Anthony Francis), both of whom toured with Olatunji's "Drums of Passion" ensemble — became the only fixed percussionists in Gabrielle Roth & The Mirrors, her musical ensemble. Sanga spent 25 years as one of Olatunji's lead djembe players and is currently described on Esalen's website as "a master drummer and living embodiment of the 5Rhythms cosmology." Roth's husband Robert Ansell played instruments explicitly including **"Yoruba and Igbo batá"** drums, alongside ashiko, dun-dun, and djembe. Esalen's own newsletter pairs them directly: "Gabrielle Roth's ecstatic dance and Babatunde Olatunji's drumming sessions used movement and rhythm to create connections and unfold epiphanies."

Roth's pivotal encounter with live drumming at Esalen became her origin story. Live percussionists "were pounding out rhythms so irresistible Roth found herself on the dance floor in spite of her knee," she later recalled. She danced until she "disappeared inside the dance" and entered "another universe, shifted into a new dimension in which there were no boundaries." This transformative experience — almost certainly involving drummers trained in or influenced by Yoruba percussion traditions — became the foundation for her entire practice. In *Maps to Ecstasy* (1989), she made the connection explicit: **"To move into chaos, I love to be carried away by tribal drumming."**

The practice is formally described as having roots in "Native American shamanic traditions, Afro-Brazilian Candomblé and Yoruba drumming." Roth called herself an "urban shaman" and described 5Rhythms as "a body of work born in the sixties that is at least seventy-five thousand years old" — a claim that simultaneously acknowledges ancient origins and erases specific cultural ownership.

