## Degas was not celebrating beauty — he was documenting a marketplace

The common museum interpretation of Edgar Degas's ballet paintings — beautiful dancers, celebration of grace, masterful capture of movement — is historically illiterate. Degas was painting the **Paris Opéra ballet as a system of institutionalized sexual exploitation**, and art historians have spent decades trying to make this clear.

The *petits rats* ("little rats") were working-class girls, some as young as ten, recruited into the Paris Opéra. They worked six days a week for minimal pay. Louis Véron, appointed Opera administrator around 1830, deliberately **decreased dancers' wages to force them to seek wealthy protectors** — institutionalizing prostitution as economic policy. The *foyer de la danse*, a lavish salon directly behind the stage, was architecturally designed as a men's club where wealthy subscribers (*abonnés*) could proposition dancers. When Charles Garnier built the Palais Garnier, he included a separate entrance for these men and designed the foyer explicitly for their access. Mothers frequently brokered arrangements for their daughters. As historian Lorraine Coons documented, even successful dancers who avoided prostitution were assumed to engage in it. A former dancer reportedly stated: "As soon as she enters the Opéra her destiny as a whore is sealed."

Degas's canvases are full of evidence. In *L'Étoile* (1878), a man in a black tuxedo lurks in the wings behind the curtsying dancer — the abonné made visible. In *The Rehearsal of the Ballet Onstage* (1874), two dark-suited men sit watching rehearsal from positions of comfort and power. His **Cardinal Monotypes** (c.1876–1880s) — approximately 40 prints illustrating his friend Ludovic Halévy's novels — make the ballet-prostitution connection completely explicit, depicting a stage mother selling her two dancing daughters. His *Little Dancer Aged Fourteen* (1881), a wax sculpture of **Marie van Goethem**, depicted a real girl whose mother was a laundress and likely prostitute, whose older sister was a sex worker. Critics called Marie "monkey-like" and said her face bore "the hateful promise of every vice." She was dismissed from the Opéra in 1882 and likely returned to sex work. The sculpture that immortalized her exploitation had no buyers in Degas's lifetime; in 2015 it was valued at approximately **$23 million**.

Feminist art historian **Eunice Lipton** (*Looking into Degas*, 1986) demonstrated that these paintings "actively carry and create meaning" about class, sex, and labor. **Jill DeVonyar** and **Richard Kendall** (*Degas and the Dance*, 2002) described the foyer de la danse as "a hunting ground where the predators/abonnés circle around the gazelles/ballerinas." Backstage access for abonnés was not banned until 1927 — to "howls of outrage."

Degas himself is not innocent in this. He said, "I have perhaps too often considered woman as an animal." Some accounts indicate he became an abonné himself. His paintings oscillate between documentation and complicity, between exposing a system and participating in the voyeurism that sustained it.

