## Effortless effort as a technology of erasure

Ballet's central aesthetic demand — that extreme physical labor appear weightless and natural — connects directly to **sprezzatura**, the Renaissance concept coined by Baldassare Castiglione in 1528: "a certain nonchalance which conceals all artistry and makes whatever one says or does seem uncontrived and effortless." When applied to female bodies in ballet, this aesthetic becomes a technology for making women's labor invisible.

**Chloe Angyal** (*Turning Pointe*, 2021) identified the connection precisely. She recognized that what Duke University researchers in 2003 called "effortless perfection" — gendered expectations requiring young women to succeed at everything while appearing not to try — "is just ballet. This is what we were taught in dance: to be athlete-strong but artist-unruffled. **To work just as hard at concealing the work as we did at the work itself.**" Edward Villella described the ideal: "steel-like legs that are doing the most fantastical feats while the upper body is soft and lovely as though nothing was going on underneath."

The physical costs are staggering. **Fifty percent** of professional ballet dancers develop disordered eating over their lifetimes. Dancers are three times more likely to develop anorexia than non-dancers. Pointe shoes — worn exclusively by women — bear the full body weight on a tiny area, causing documented injuries, chronic pain, and long-term musculoskeletal damage. A 2023 study found ballet institutions actively teach dancers to "normalise physical pain." Training totals 20–39 hours per week. Women have greater injury prevalence than men due to higher technical requirements, while **72% of artistic directors are men** and 81% of the world's most prestigious companies are led by men. In 2016, New York City Ballet performed 58 ballets — not one choreographed by a woman.

High heels replicate the same logic. Originating as **Persian cavalry footwear** (functional, masculine, military), heels were adopted by European aristocrats — Louis XIV, only 5'4", made red heels a mark of courtly status. As heels became feminized in the 18th century, they shifted from power symbols to aesthetic constraints. A 2023 systematic review of 33 studies found high heels significantly alter gait, shorten the Achilles tendon, increase back pain, and reduce postural stability. High-heel injuries nearly doubled from 2002 to 2012. Yet 37–69% of women wear them daily. Both ballet and heels began as male domains, were feminized, and in feminization became mechanisms for displaying constraint as elegance.

